<meta name="title" content="Stamford fire service consolidation part of Malloy's legacy"/>
<meta name="description" content="Fourteen years later, and after several lawsuits and heated public debates over the future of firefighting in Stamford, many of those attempts were left unfinished -- or undone through court rulings.  To cover a decreasing pool of active volunteers among Stamford's Big Five, the five volunteer-run departments granted autonomy and funding by the city Charter, Malloy's administration looked toward the city department, Stamford Fire &amp; Rescue, to supply the firehouses north of downtown with more manpower.  In a large district in central Stamford, two city engine companies run out of steel garages built after Turn of River went all-volunteer in summer 2008, voting down an agreement with the city over a proposed merger with Stamford Fire &amp; Rescue.  The merger was introduced in 2007 and caused an uproar among volunteer fire officials, who saw it as an attempt to dismantle the volunteer fire system in Stamford, a system protected by the Charter since the city and town of Stamford become a single municipality in the 1940s.  [...] volunteer fire officials said his attempts were unilateral and claimed they violated the city Charter and contracts with the departments.  Paid firefighters at Belltown and Turn of River were assimilated in Stamford Fire &amp; Rescue because they were considered city employees under the same labor contract as city firefighters, leaving the two departments with volunteers only.  The settlement with Belltown leaves one outstanding litigation between the city and a volunteer fire department: the city's lawsuit challenging the legitimacy of the Turn of River fire marshal."/>


